          "body": "The Jebusite declaration — 'You shall not enter here' (11:5) — is the chapter's first moment of direct opposition, and its brevity signals how quickly it is overcome. The Jebusites' confidence in their stronghold is the confidence of those who have not reckoned with the LORD of hosts. David's capture of Zion is presented without elaborate military detail; the Chronicler is not interested in the tactics. What he preserves is the outcome: David dwells in the stronghold (11:7), he builds the city from the Millo outward (11:8), and then comes the chapter's theological anchor — 'David became greater and greater, for the LORD of hosts was with him' (11:9). The divine title 'LORD of hosts' (Yahweh tsava) is the military name of God — the commander of heaven's armies. David's growing greatness is explicitly attributed to Yahweh's personal attendance, not to David's own genius or strength. This is the Chronicler's consistent pattern throughout the book: human flourishing is a sacrament of divine presence. The title 'City of David' (11:7) will carry enormous weight through the rest of Chronicles and into the New Testament (Luke 2:11), where it names the birthplace of the son of David who is greater than David."
