          "title": "The water poured out — valor consecrated",
          "body": "The episode of the Bethlehem water (11:15-19) is the chapter's most theologically dense narrative and its most humanly moving. Three of the Thirty break through a Philistine garrison — risking death — to fulfill a casual wish David had expressed for water from his hometown well. When they return, David refuses to drink it. His refusal is not ingratitude; it is theological precision: 'Shall I drink the blood of these men who went at the risk of their lives?' The equation is striking — water fetched at the cost of a life is blood, and blood belongs to God (Leviticus 17:11; Genesis 9:4). David pours it out as a libation to the LORD. The act simultaneously honors the men (their sacrifice is too great for David to consume as a personal pleasure), honors the LORD (their lives belong to Him), and reveals David's character: he will not exploit loyalty for private comfort. Swindoll rightly notes that great leaders are those who cannot separate the cost of their followers' service from their own enjoyment of its benefits. David's gesture is the inverse of the Saul narrative — where Saul repeatedly consumed what did not belong to him (1 Samuel 15:9). The water poured out is the chapter's most concentrated image of what the kingdom of God looks like: human courage offered, human pride refused, and everything consecrated to Yahweh."
