    "intro": "Interpretation moves from what the text says to what it means — from surface observation to authorial intent within canonical context. 1 Chronicles 11 is the Chronicler's programmatic opening of the Davidic narrative, and its meaning is inseparable from its post-exilic purpose: to ground a community without a king in the unshakeable word of Yahweh concerning the Davidic covenant. The movements below trace the chapter's argument from the anointing at Hebron through the capture of Jerusalem to the theology embedded in the roster of the mighty men.",
