        "title": "Anointed according to the word — the divine word precedes and governs the human ceremony",
        "range": "11:1-3",
        "excerpt": "They anointed David king over Israel, according to the word of the LORD through Samuel.",
        "body": "The opening three verses of 1 Chronicles 11 perform a theological operation that the Chronicler's post-exilic audience would have recognized immediately. By omitting 2 Samuel 1-4 entirely — the lamentation over Saul, the civil war between Ish-bosheth and David, the two-year interregnum — the Chronicler presents Israel's acceptance of David as instantaneous and unanimous. This is not historical naivety; it is theological selectivity in service of a pastoral argument. The post-exilic community needed to know that the unified Davidic kingdom was not an accident of political maneuvering but the direct expression of divine will.\n\nIsrael's speech in 11:1-2 is structured as a two-part argument: a kinship claim ('we are your bone and your flesh') and a historical observation ('even when Saul was king, you were the one who led out and brought in Israel'). The first claim is the language of covenant relationship — the same phrase Adam uses of Eve in Genesis 2:23, signaling that a bond of shared nature and mutual belonging grounds the relationship. The second claim is an admission: Israel already knew David was their real leader before the coronation made it official. Providence had been visible for years; the ceremony catches up to the reality.\n\nThe crucial phrase is the closing of verse 3: 'according to the word of the LORD through Samuel.' The anointing is not self-generated by popular acclaim or political calculation. It ratifies a prior prophetic word (1 Samuel 16:1-13). The Chronicler uses this phrase structurally — it will reappear at 11:10 to encompass the entire roster of mighty men. Everything in the chapter is 'according to' this word. For the post-exilic community, this is the most important hermeneutical claim in the chapter: the Davidic covenant does not depend on the continued presence of a Davidic king on the throne. It depends on the word of Yahweh, which does not return void (Isaiah 55:11).\n\nThe covenant David makes with the elders 'before the LORD' at Hebron (11:3) is significant because it is mutual and witnessed. David's authority is not absolute or unaccountable — it is covenant-shaped, publicly ratified, and executed in Yahweh's presence. This framing anticipates the Davidic covenant of 2 Samuel 7 / 1 Chronicles 17, where the LORD will formalize His own obligations to the house of David. The earthly covenant at Hebron mirrors the divine covenant that will follow.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Davar Yahweh* (word of the LORD, 11:3) — the authoritative divine speech that generates history. *Berit* (covenant, 11:3) — a binding agreement with defined obligations and divine witnesses. *Mashach* (anointed, 11:3) — the same root as *mashiach* (messiah, anointed one); every anointing of a Davidic king is a type anticipating the final Anointed One (Psalm 2:2; Acts 4:26)."
